Evidence in page: 
Ernst Stuhlinger (December 19, 1913 – May 25, 2008) was a German-American atomic, electrical, and rocket scientist. After being brought to the United States as part of Operation Paperclip, he developed guidance systems with Wernher von Braun's team for the US Army, and later was a scientist with NASA. He was also instrumental in the development of the ion engine for long-endurance space flight, and a wide variety of scientific experiments.

Stuhlinger was born in Niederrimbach (now part of Creglingen), Württemberg, Germany. At age 23, he earned his doctorate in physics at the University of Tübingen in 1936... In 1939 to 1941, he worked in Berlin, on cosmic rays and nuclear physics as an assistant professor at Technische Hochschule Berlin... drafted as a private in the German Army and sent to the Russian front... Upon reaching German territory in 1943, Stuhlinger was ordered to the rocket development center in Peenemünde where he joined Dr. Wernher von Braun's team.

Stuhlinger was one of the first group of 126 scientists who emigrated to the United States with von Braun after World War II as part of Operation Paperclip. From 1945 to 1950 he primarily worked on guidance systems in US Army missile programs at Fort Bliss, Texas... He eventually served as director of the Advanced Research Projects Division of the Army Ballistic Missile Agency (ABMA)... On April 14, 1955, together with many other Paperclip members, he became a naturalized United States citizen.

On the night of January 31, 1958, Stuhlinger was at the controls of the timer when the Explorer 1 was launched, triggering the device right on time. He became known as "the man with the golden finger."

In 1960, the major part of ABMA was transferred to NASA, forming the Marshall Space Flight Center (MSFC) in Huntsville, Alabama. Stuhlinger served as director of the MSFC Space Science Laboratory from its formation in 1960 until 1968, and then was MSFC's associate director for science from 1968 to 1975.

Stuhlinger spent much of his spare time developing designs for solar-powered spacecraft. The most popular of those designs relied on ion thrusters... He is considered as one of the pioneers of electric propulsion... Starting in 1990, Stuhlinger and Frederick I. Ordway III collaborated on the two-volume biography Wernher von Braun: Crusader for Space (Krieger Publishing, 1994).

Summary: 
Ernst Stuhlinger (1913–2008) was a pioneering German-American atomic, electrical, and rocket scientist. Earning his doctorate in physics in 1936, he initially worked on cosmic rays before being drafted into the German Army during WWII. Surviving the Russian front, he joined Wernher von Braun's rocket team in Peenemünde. Post-war, he immigrated to the U.S. via Operation Paperclip, becoming a naturalized citizen in 1955. Stuhlinger played a critical role in early U.S. space efforts, famously triggering the staging timer for Explorer 1, earning the nickname 'the man with the golden finger.' He directed the Marshall Space Flight Center's Space Science Laboratory (1960–1968) and made significant contributions to the development of ion engines and electric propulsion. In his later years, he served as a university professor and co-authored a biography of Wernher von Braun. This comprehensive overview provides key details for verifying any specific clues regarding his life and career.
